<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many drywall screws per 4x8 sheet?", answer: "Walls screwed at 16\" OC edges and 24\" OC field need about 32 screws per 4×8 sheet. Walls with tighter 12\" OC field spacing need about 40. Ceilings always need more — 48 screws per sheet at 12\" OC edges and field. Adhesive installations need only about 16 screws per sheet (top and bottom of each stud) since the adhesive carries most of the load." },
  { question: "What size drywall screws do I need?", answer: "1-1/4\" coarse thread for 1/2\" drywall over wood framing — the standard size. 1-5/8\" for 5/8\" drywall. 1\" for 3/8\" drywall. Use fine-thread screws for steel framing. Always drive screws until the head slightly dimples the paper face without breaking through — a screw gun with an adjustable clutch does this automatically." },
  { question: "How many pounds of drywall screws do I need?", answer: "A typical 1-1/4\" coarse drywall screw weighs about 1.6 grams, so there are about 280 screws per pound. A 2,000 sq ft job (about 60 sheets) at 32 screws each = 1,920 screws = roughly 7 pounds. Always buy 1 extra pound for waste, strip-outs, and spares. 5-pound and 25-pound boxes are the standard retail sizes." },
  { question: "Do ceiling installations need more screws?", answer: "Yes — ceilings hold drywall up against gravity, so the pattern is denser: 12\" OC on all edges and field, vs 16\"/24\" on walls. A 4×8 ceiling sheet needs about 48 screws (compared to 32 for the same size wall sheet). Always use 1-5/8\" screws on ceilings (or 2\" for heavy 5/8\" Type X firerated), and never skimp — a ceiling falling is a serious injury hazard." },
  { question: "Can I use nails instead of screws?", answer: "Yes for walls but screws are the modern standard and hold better. Nail schedule is 7\" OC edges and 8\" OC field for walls, 7\" everywhere for ceilings, and requires 2× as many nails vs screws because nails pop out over time. Most pros go screws-only now except for fire-rated assemblies where nail fastening may be code-required." }
]) %>

